      <h3>The Thought Process Behind Neo‑Brutalism</h3>
      <p>
        Neo-brutalism in web design is anti-polish and anti-corporate. It embraces honesty, rawness,
        and structural transparency. The style intentionally removes decorative elements and
        focuses on clear geometry, bold contrast, and visual bluntness.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <div class="learn-cards">
    <article class="card learn-secondary-card purple">
      <div class="learn-secondary-inner">
        <h4>Color Choice Is Deliberately Harsh</h4>
        <p>
          Neo-brutalism uses:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Pure black (<code>#000</code>)</li>
          <li>Pure white (<code>#FFF</code>)</li>
          <li>Flat primaries like bright red (<code>#FF0000</code>), blue (<code>#0000FF</code>), yellow (<code>#FFFF00</code>)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          These colors reflect:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Intensity (saturated hues)</li>
          <li>Simplicity (minimal variety)</li>
          <li>High contrast (black vs white)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          This creates a feeling of directness and visual truth—a reaction against soft UI trends like glassmorphism or neumorphism.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
    <article class="card learn-secondary-card alt">
      <div class="learn-secondary-inner">
        <h4>Borders Replace Shadows</h4>
        <p>
          Instead of using shadows to create depth, neo-brutalism uses:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Thick black lines</li>
          <li>Boxed-in elements</li>
          <li>High-contrast outlines</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          This reflects a belief that structure should be visible, not hidden behind smooth gradients.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
    <article class="card learn-skinny-card">
      <div class="learn-secondary-inner">
        <h5>Purposefully “Ugly” Choices</h5>
        <p>Many neo-brutalist choices go against traditional color theory to communicate authenticity:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Using clashing colors</li>
          <li>Overly bright hues</li>
          <li>Sparse neutral tones</li>
          <li>Minimal shading or blending</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Breaking color harmony is an intentional stylistic choice that makes the design feel unfiltered and expressive.</p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>

